http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: In the spring of 2010, the Oregon Association of School Libraries (OASL) called for the establishment of a committee to write school library standards. A select group of public and private school teacher-librarians/media specialists from around the state researched and studied the American Association of School Librarians (AASL) guidelines, library standards articulated by other states, and existing grade level library standards from various school districts both in and out of state. They went through a process of study, synthesis and writing, drawing on the professional and collective wisdom of experts in the area of K-12 library instruction, reading and technology use. Together, the committee identified four instructional areas necessary for a robust library program: Information Literacy; Reading Engagement; Social Responsibility and Technology Integration. On January 22, 2015, the State Board of Education voted unanimously to adopt the Oregon School Library Standards.

Follow an inquiry-based process to seek knowledge
Apply prior knowledge to new learning
Develop, select, clarify and use questions and strategies to search for information
Find, evaluate and select appropriate sources to answer questions
Select appropriate digital and other information tools for accessing content
Evaluate information for accuracy, validity, importance and bias
Read, view and listen to information in a variety of formats
Collaborate to broaden and deepen understanding
Assess the effectiveness of questions, strategies and processes used in research to find information
Use skills, resources and tools to draw conclusions, make informed decisions, create new knowledge and apply knowledge to new situations.
Analyze and evaluate information to draw conclusions and make informed decisions
Analyze, organize and synthesize information using a variety of tools
Use information to answer questions, solve real-world problems and inspire further investigation
Collaborate with others to exchange ideas, develop new understandings, make decisions and solve problems
Reach and defend informed conclusions based on best evidence.
Evaluate the effectiveness of the skills and tools used to create new knowledge
Use skills, resources and tools to create and share work that expresses and demonstrates new understandings
Analyze delivery formats for sharing understanding
Use appropriate tools to create and share new work
Collaborate with others to create original products and share new understanding
Reflect on a product's effectiveness in expressing and demonstrating new understanding

Read, listen to, and view a variety of genres and formats

Read to answer questions, make decisions or solve problems
Explore text to text, text to self, and text to world connections
Appreciate and evaluate author's craft and use of literary devices
Read to seek multiple points of view and a global perspective
Comprehend, interpret and evaluate informational and fictional text
Read, listen to, view and integrate information to build background knowledge
Demonstrate reading for meaning, evaluate evidence, find the main and supporting details, form opinions and draw conclusions
Read to evaluate history, current events and personal decisions
Evaluate text for author's purpose
Build reading skills and behaviors for life-long learning
Apply reading strategies across the content areas
Contribute to a reading and learning community
Self-select reading materials from a variety of genres and formats
Make personal connections to the real world when reading a variety of texts
Demonstrate resiliency, perseverance and stamina when reading a variety of texts

Use appropriate language when communicating with others
Participate in and advocate for safe and ethical communication
Practice accuracy and consider bias when sharing information
Practice ethical behavior when using print and digital resources
Consider a variety of balanced and authoritative sources

Avoid plagiarism and respect the intellectual property of others when gathering, presenting or publishing information.
Participate collaboratively, respectfully and productively as a member of a democratic society
Collaborate as members of a social and intellectual community
Advocate for intellectual freedom and uphold the rights of others
Demonstrate responsible citizenship in use of materials and resources

Evaluate digital information sources for accuracy, validity, importance and bias

Use digital tools to analyze and organize information

Explore digital tools to create and share works that express and demonstrate new understandings
Use a variety of digital environments and formats to enhance reading engagement
Explore a variety of digital tools and formats to develop an appreciation for reading
Participate in reading and learning communities online
Use digital tools and resources to self-select reading materials from a variety of genres and formats
Practice ethical behavior when using technology
Use appropriate language when communicating with others in digital environments

Avoid plagiarism and respect the intellectual property of others when gathering, presenting or publishing information.
